data.content:
Here's the performance review for this hot-path logging library.

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace()` (3+) | 0 |
| `params` | 2 |
| `.Substring()` | 0 |
| `.IndexOf(string)` no comparison | 0 |
| LINQ operators (`.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate`) | 16 |
| `.Any()` | 1 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 3 |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| `Enumerable.Reverse` | 1 |
| `Enum.GetValues` | 1 |
| Unsealed non-static classes | 1 of 1 |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| Sync-over-async | 0 |
| String interpolation | 3 |

---

## Findings

### 🔴 Critical

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Every Call (16 operator sites + delegates)

**Impact:** At millions of calls/min, each `Humanize()` invocation allocates 5–8 enumerators, 3–4 delegate objects, and intermediate collections. This dominates GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128`, `L140`, `L143`, `L146`, `L149`, `L158`, `L169`, `L244`, `L261–262`, `L270–272`, `L284`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops writing into pre-sized `Span<T>` or stack-allocated buffers. For example, `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan`:

```csharp
// Before (3 enumerator + delegate allocations + list materialization)
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}

// After (zero LINQ allocations)
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int taken = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (taken >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) taken++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) taken++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

Similarly, `IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128) should be a `foreach` loop instead of `.Any()`, and `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L158) should iterate directly instead of `.Where().ToList()`.

---

#### 2. `Enum.ToString()` + `.ToLowerInvariant()` — 3 Allocations per Time Unit (compound)

**Impact:** `FormatTimePart` (L174–176) calls `unit.ToString()` (boxes enum → allocates string), then `.ToLowerInvariant()` (second string), then string interpolation (third string). Called once per non-zero time unit per log entry — up to 8× per `Humanize()` call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175–176`

**Fix:** Cache lowercase unit names in a static array indexed by enum ordinal:

```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];
private static readonly string[] s_unitNamesPlural =
    ["years", "months", "weeks", "days", "hours", "minutes", "seconds", "milliseconds"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture) =>
    $"{value} {(value == 1 ? s_unitNames[(int)unit] : s_unitNamesPlural[(int)unit])}";
```

This eliminates 2 of 3 allocations per call. To eliminate the third (interpolation), use `string.Concat(value.ToString(), " ", name)` or cache fully-formatted strings for small values of `value`.

---

### 🟡 Moderate

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` Allocates Array per Call (2 instances)

**Impact:** Every call to `Transform()` allocates a `T[]`, even for the common 1-argument case. On a hot path, this is one avoidable allocation per call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload (or use `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` on .NET 9+):

```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

---

#### 4. `HumanizeDisplayStrings` — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` Chain (compound)

**Impact:** Three chained LINQ operators (L270–272) allocate 2 enumerators, 2 delegates, plus a final `ToArray()` materializing an array. Each `Humanize<T>` call pays this cost.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L269–272`

**Fix:** Replace with a `foreach` loop building a `List<string>` (or use `ArrayPool`):

```csharp
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.Trim();
        if (trimmed.Length > 0) items.Add(trimmed);
    }
    // ... join logic
}
```

---

#### 5. Double `.Select()` Chain in Object-Formatter Overload

**Impact:** The `Func<T, object?>` overload (L259–263) chains two `.Select()` calls — two enumerator + delegate allocations — to convert `object? → string?`. These feed into `HumanizeDisplayStrings` which adds another `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L260–263`

**Fix:** Merge into a single `.Select(o => objectFormatter(o)?.ToString())` to halve the enumerator cost, or better, use a `foreach` loop in `HumanizeDisplayStrings` that accepts `Func<T, object?>` directly.

---

### ℹ️ Info

#### 6. `DefaultCollectionFormatter` Not Sealed (1 of 1 classes)

**Impact:** Prevents JIT devirtualization of `virtual` `Humanize` methods. However, the class has `virtual` methods suggesting it is designed for inheritance — sealing would be a breaking API change.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`

**Fix:** If no subclasses exist, add `sealed`. Otherwise, leave as-is.

**Caveat:** Only seal if no consumers inherit from this class.

---

#### 7. Static Init LINQ (`Enumerable.Reverse` + `Enum.GetValues`)

**Impact:** One-time allocation at class load — not a per-call cost. Negligible for runtime performance.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L41`

**Fix:** Replace with a reversed array literal for clarity: `[TimeUnit.Millisecond, ..., TimeUnit.Year]`.

---

## Positive Patterns

- ✅ No sync-over-async blocking
- ✅ No `.Substring()` allocations
- ✅ No `string.Format` boxing
- ✅ No regex usage
- ✅ `List<string?>(8)` pre-sized at L91
- ✅ `culture ??=` avoids redundant allocations

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 | 16 LINQ operator sites allocating enumerators/delegates per call; `Enum.ToString()` + `.ToLowerInvariant()` compound allocation |
| 🟡 Moderate | 3 | `params` array allocation; `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chains; double `.Select()` |
| ℹ️ Info | 2 | Unsealed class with virtual methods; one-time static init LINQ |

**Highest-impact fix:** Eliminating LINQ from `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan`, `IsContainingOnlyNullValue`, `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts`, and `HumanizeDisplayStrings` would remove ~8 enumerator + delegate allocations per call — the single biggest source of GC pressure at millions of calls/minute. Caching unit name strings is the second-highest win.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
